### 9. Default color in panel doesn't match rendered color (Gluestack internal tokens)

**Root cause:** Gluestack components like Button apply colors via internal CSS class tokens (`bg-primary-500`). These aren't extractable from `node.props.className`, so the color pickers showed `#ffffff` / `#000000` as defaults even when the component rendered blue.

**Fix:** Use a `useEffect` in `DesignTab` to read `window.getComputedStyle()` from the live DOM element after each render, then convert `rgb(r,g,b)` → hex. Store in local state (`computedBgColor`, `computedTextColor`, `computedBorderColor`). Pass these as the default values to `ColorInput`.

**Rule:** Never hardcode `#ffffff` as the default for a color input. Always read the real computed style from the DOM. Transparent (`rgba(0,0,0,0)`) should fall back to `#ffffff`.

---

### 10. Inline text editing — double-click on canvas

**Feature:** Double-clicking a `Text`, `Heading`, or `ButtonText` node on the canvas opens a floating `<textarea>` positioned exactly over the element. The font size scales with the current zoom level. On blur or Escape the edit is committed/cancelled.

**Implementation:** `_canvas.tsx` tracks `editingId`, `editingText`, `editingRect`. The capture overlay's `onDoubleClick` handler walks up the DOM tree looking for a node whose type is in `TEXT_NODE_TYPES`. The textarea is rendered with `position: absolute` within the canvas div using the node's `getBoundingClientRect()` minus the canvas rect.

**Rule:** When `editingId` is set, the capture overlay's `onPointerDown` commits the edit and returns early (so clicking outside saves and exits).

---

### 11. Content section in right panel (text editing)

**Feature:** When a Text, Heading, or ButtonText node is selected, a "Content" section appears at the top of the Design panel with a `<textarea>` that edits `node.text` via `patchProp(nodeId, 'text', value)`. For Button nodes, it finds the first `ButtonText` child and edits that instead.

**Rule:** Use `patchProp(id, 'text', value)` not `patchProp(id, 'props.text', value)` — the `text` field is at the node root level, not inside `props`.

---

### 13. Hug / Fill does nothing when node was previously resized

**Root cause:** Clicking Hug (`w-fit`) or Fill (`w-full`) only patched `className`. But if the node was resized via drag handles or the W/H number input, it has `style.width: "100px"` as an inline style. Inline styles have higher CSS specificity than any class, so `w-full` / `w-fit` were silently ignored.

**Fix:** Hug and Fill click handlers now call `patchStyle({ width: '', minWidth: '' })` (or `height/minHeight`) in addition to updating the className. Fixed mode intentionally does NOT clear the inline style — it preserves the user's explicit size.

**Rule:** Any time you add a layout-mode class (`w-fit`, `w-full`, `h-fit`, `h-full`) you must also clear the corresponding inline style property. Otherwise the inline style wins.

---

### 12. Min/Max Width and Height

**Feature:** Dimensions section now includes 4 extra NumberInputs (Min W, Max W, Min H, Max H) that set `style.minWidth`, `style.maxWidth`, `style.minHeight`, `style.maxHeight` as pixel values. Setting to 0 clears the constraint.

**Rule:** Use inline style for these (not Tailwind `min-w-*` tokens) to allow exact pixel values.

---

### 14. Drag ghost: original element visible during drag (double-image)

**Root cause:** When dragging a non-absolute node, the browser shows a ghost copy following the cursor AND the original element stays fully opaque in place — creating a duplicate.

**Fix:** In `onDragStart` (non-absolute path), one `requestAnimationFrame` after calling `setDragImage` (so the ghost snapshot is captured at full opacity), set `nodeEl.style.opacity = '0.3'` for all dragged elements and store them in `draggedElRef = useRef<HTMLElement[]>([])`. Restore in both `onDrop` and `onDragEnd` by iterating `draggedElRef.current`.

**Key subtlety — `onDrop` clears the ref first:** `onDrop` sets `draggingNodeIdRef.current = null` before `onDragEnd` fires. So `onDragEnd` cannot query by node ID to restore opacity. Fix: use a dedicated `draggedElRef` (array of DOM elements) that is independent of `draggingNodeIdRef`. Both `onDrop` and `onDragEnd` clear it — whichever fires first wins, the second is a no-op.

**Rule:** Never restore drag opacity via `draggingNodeIdRef` — that ref is cleared in `onDrop` before `onDragEnd` fires. Always use `draggedElRef` (the actual DOM elements captured at drag-start).

**Ghost size inflation (canvas zoom) + composite ghost for multi-drag:**

`setDragImage(nodeEl, ox, oy)` where `nodeEl` is inside a `transform: scale(zoom)` container captures the element at its SCREEN size (= CSS size × zoom). At zoom > 1 the ghost is inflated.

Fix: build a ghost `div` appended to `document.body` (outside the scaled canvas) from clones of all dragged elements, positioned at their relative screen-space positions divided by `zoom`:

```ts
const rects = allDragIds.map(id => ({
  el:   document.querySelector(`[data-builder-id="${id}"]`) as HTMLElement,
  rect: document.querySelector(`[data-builder-id="${id}"]`)?.getBoundingClientRect(),
})).filter(r => r.el && r.rect);

const minX = Math.min(...rects.map(r => r.rect.left));
const minY = Math.min(...rects.map(r => r.rect.top));

const ghostEl = document.createElement('div');
ghostEl.style.cssText = `position:fixed;left:-9999px;top:-9999px;pointer-events:none;width:${(maxX-minX)/zoom}px;height:${(maxY-minY)/zoom}px;`;
document.body.appendChild(ghostEl);

for (const { el, rect } of rects) {
  const clone = el.cloneNode(true) as HTMLElement;
  clone.style.position = 'absolute';
  clone.style.left  = `${(rect.left - minX) / zoom}px`;
  clone.style.top   = `${(rect.top  - minY) / zoom}px`;
  clone.style.width  = `${rect.width  / zoom}px`;
  clone.style.height = `${rect.height / zoom}px`;
  clone.style.transform = '';
  ghostEl.appendChild(clone);
}

e.dataTransfer.setDragImage(ghostEl, (e.clientX - minX) / zoom, (e.clientY - minY) / zoom);
requestAnimationFrame(() => { document.body.removeChild(ghostEl); /* then fade originals */ });
```

**Rules:**
- Always divide screen coordinates by `zoom` when building a ghost that lives outside the canvas.
- For multi-drag, always build the composite ghost from ALL `allDragIds`, not just the primary node — this shows all selected elements moving together (Figma-style).

---

### 15. Resize handles float over the drag ghost

**Root cause:** `BuilderOverlay` was not aware that a drag was in progress, so it kept rendering selection rings and resize handles on top of the ghost image.

**Fix:** Added `isDragging: boolean` state to `_canvas.tsx` — set to `true` inside the `requestAnimationFrame` of `onDragStart`, cleared in both `onDrop` and `onDragEnd`. Pass `isDragging` as a prop to `BuilderOverlay`. In the overlay, gate the hover outline, single-selection ring, resize handles, multi-select highlights, crosshairs, and dimension tooltip behind `!isDragging`.

**Rule:** Any new overlay element that would look wrong while dragging (e.g. labels, handles, distance lines) must also be gated with `!isDragging`.

---

### 18. Stale marquee-select after drag from empty canvas space

**Root cause:** `onPointerDown` (canvas background) sets `marqueeStartRef.current` whenever a click lands on empty canvas (no node under cursor). When you then drag nodes that are already selected (via the `selectedIds` fallback in `onDragStart`), the HTML5 drag takes over and the browser stops firing pointer events — so `onPointerUp` (which normally clears `marqueeStartRef`) **never fires**. On the next mouse-move the engine still thinks a marquee is active and draws the selection rectangle.

**Fix:**
1. `onDragStart` — at the very top, clear `marqueeStartRef.current` and call `setMarquee(null)`.
2. `onDragEnd` — clear them again as a safety net.

```ts
// onDragStart (first lines):
if (marqueeStartRef.current) {
  marqueeStartRef.current = null;
  setMarquee(null);
}
```

**Rule:** Any code path that transitions from pointer-down → HTML5 drag must clear `marqueeStartRef` immediately in `onDragStart`, because the browser eats the `pointerup` event that would normally do the cleanup.

---

### 16. Multi-select drag: clicking a selected node deselects others before drag starts

**Root cause:** The capture overlay's `onPointerDown` called `select(hit.id, e.shiftKey)` unconditionally. Without shift, this replaced the entire multi-selection with just the clicked node — so by the time `onDragStart` fired, `selectedIds` only ever had one entry.

**Fix:** Guard in `onPointerDown`:
```tsx
if (hit.kind === 'node') {
  const { selectedIds: curIds } = useBuilderStore.getState();
  // Only change selection if the node isn't already selected (or shift is held).
  // Preserve multi-selection for drag; onPointerUp reduces it if no drag occurred.
  if (!curIds.includes(hit.id) || e.shiftKey) {
    select(hit.id, e.shiftKey);
  }
}
```
`onPointerUp` already handles reducing multi-selection to single on a plain click with no drag.

**Rule:** `onPointerDown` on the capture overlay must NEVER replace an existing multi-selection when the clicked node is already selected without shift — doing so destroys multi-select drag before it starts.

---

### 17. Multi-select drag: only one node moves on drop

**Root cause:** `onDrop` always called `moveNode(singleId, ...)` — no path for moving multiple selected nodes.

**Fix:**
1. Added `moveNodes(nodeIds[], newParentId, atIdx)` to `_store.ts` — removes all specified nodes in one pass, then inserts them consecutively at the target. Adjusts `atIdx` by counting how many of the moved nodes were already before the target index in the destination parent.
2. In `onDragStart`, computed `allDragIds = selectedIds.includes(dragId) && selectedIds.length > 1 ? [...selectedIds] : [dragId]` and stored it in `multiDragIdsRef`.
3. In `onDrop`, when `multiDragIdsRef.current.length > 1`, call `moveNodes(allIds, ...)` instead of `moveNode`.
4. All nodes in `allDragIds` are faded (opacity 0.3) during drag; all are restored on `onDrop`/`onDragEnd`.

**Rule:** Any drag-and-drop operation that could involve multiple selected nodes must use `moveNodes` (not repeated `moveNode` calls). Repeated single moves cause index drift and incorrect ordering.

**Additional guard — topmost-only filter:** `moveNodes` must filter `nodeIds` to only the topmost nodes before moving. If a marquee-selection includes both a parent (e.g. `Button`) and its child (e.g. `ButtonText`), naively moving both independently inserts `ButtonText` as a sibling of `Button` — outside Gluestack's Button context — causing a hard crash (`useStyleContext` returns undefined). Fix: before collecting `nodesToMove`, walk each node's ancestor chain; if any ancestor is also in the move set, skip that node (it will ride along inside its ancestor's cloned subtree).

```typescript
const nodeIdSet = new Set(nodeIds);
const topMostIds = nodeIds.filter(id => {
  let parent = findParentNode(s.pageNodes, id);
  while (parent !== null && parent !== undefined) {
    if (nodeIdSet.has(parent.id ?? '')) return false; // ancestor also moving
    parent = findParentNode(s.pageNodes, parent.id ?? '');
  }
  return true;
});
// use topMostIds instead of nodeIds for nodesToMove
```

