## §19 Multi-Drag Self-Drop Guard

**Root cause:** The `isDroppingSelf` / `isDroppingIntoSelf` checks in `onDragOver` only examined `draggingNodeIdRef.current` — a single ID (the primary drag handle node). When dragging two buttons (btn-a primary, btn-b secondary), hovering over btn-b passed both checks and registered btn-b as a valid "drop inside" container — allowing the user to drop the selection into one of the selected nodes themselves.

**Fix — `onDragOver` (UI layer):**
Build a `Set` from `multiDragIdsRef.current` and check every dragged ID:
```typescript
const allDraggingIds = multiDragIdsRef.current.length > 0
  ? multiDragIdsRef.current
  : (draggingId ? [draggingId] : []);
const draggingIdSet = new Set(allDraggingIds);

const isDroppingSelf = draggingIdSet.has(nodeId);          // target is one of the dragged nodes
const isDroppingIntoSelf = isContainer &&
  allDraggingIds.some(id => !!findNode((nodeInTree?.children ?? []) as SDUINode[], id));
```
When `isDroppingSelf` is true the hover falls through to the before/after reorder path instead (still valid behaviour).

**Fix — `moveNodes` (store layer, defense-in-depth):**
Before any tree mutation, bail out early if `newParentId` is one of the nodes being moved:
```typescript
const nodeIdSet0 = new Set(nodeIds);
if (newParentId && nodeIdSet0.has(newParentId)) return s; // cyclic drop → no-op
```

**Rule:** Both the UI guard (`onDragOver`) and the store guard (`moveNodes`) must reject cyclic drops. The UI guard prevents the drop indicator from showing; the store guard prevents any caller from accidentally completing the operation.

